---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const faq = [
  {
    q: "What is PRAANA?",
    a: "PRAANA is an open-source terminal coding agent. It runs in your CLI, calls an LLM, executes tools (code search, multi-file edits with diff preview, optional shell), keeps long sessions usable with adaptive context, and remembers useful learnings across sessions in a local database.",
  },
  {
    q: "Which LLM providers does PRAANA work with?",
    a: "Anthropic (Claude), OpenAI (GPT), DeepSeek, Groq, Google (Gemini), Mistral, xAI, Fireworks, Together, OpenCode, and OpenRouter, plus Ollama for fully local models. PRAANA auto-detects your provider API key from the environment.",
  },
  {
    q: "How is PRAANA different from a plain transcript coding agent?",
    a: "An opt-in engine mode keeps long sessions on track with tiered working memory and tool-output distillation instead of stuffing the full history into the prompt. Optional cognitive memory extracts learnings when a session ends and surfaces a ranked digest at the start of the next. Known limitations are published upfront and there are no benchmark claims we can't back.",
  },
  {
    q: "Is PRAANA free and open source?",
    a: "Yes. PRAANA is MIT-licensed, the source is on GitHub, and it is published on npm. Install it with bunx praana or bun add -g praana.",
  },
  {
    q: "Does my data leave my machine?",
    a: "PRAANA is local-first. Cognitive memory lives in a local SQLite database on your machine. The only network calls are to the LLM provider you choose, or none at all if you run a local model with Ollama.",
  },
  {
    q: "What do I need to run PRAANA?",
    a: "Bun ≥ 1.2 (bun.sh/install) and an API key for any supported provider, or Ollama for fully local use.",
  },
];

const faqStructuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  mainEntity: faq.map(({ q, a }) => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    name: q,
    acceptedAnswer: { "@type": "Answer", text: a },
  })),
};
---

<Layout title="PRAANA" current="home">
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>PRAANA</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      A terminal coding agent that <strong>manages context like memory</strong>. It curates what the model sees on every turn and stores learnings across sessions in a local SQLite database. Pure TypeScript, local-first. Works with Claude, GPT, Gemini, DeepSeek, Groq, Mistral, Ollama and more.
    </p>
    <img src={`${base}assets/demo.png`} alt="PRAANA terminal coding agent demo" width="720" height="auto" />
  </section>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      PRAANA runs in your terminal, calls an LLM, executes tools, and tries to keep long sessions
      usable by compressing old context instead of stuffing everything into the prompt. Between
      sessions it can extract learnings from transcripts and store them in a local SQLite database.
    </p>

    <h2>Install</h2>
    <pre><code>npm install -g praana
export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="sk-ant-..."   # or OPENAI_API_KEY, OPENROUTER_API_KEY, ...
praana</code></pre>
    <p>
      Requires <strong>Node 22+</strong>. See the
      <a href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana#quick-start">README</a> for all providers
      and config options.
    </p>

    <h2>Documentation</h2>
    <div class="card-grid">
      <a class="card" href={`${base}architecture/`}>
        <strong>Architecture</strong>
        <span>Adaptive context, cognitive memory, turn flow</span>
      </a>
      <a class="card" href={`${base}concepts/`}>
        <strong>Concepts</strong>
        <span>Glossary and mental model</span>
      </a>
      <a class="card" href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana/blob/main/ROADMAP.md">
        <strong>Roadmap</strong>
        <span>Direction and honest limitations</span>
      </a>
      <a class="card" href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md">
        <strong>Contributing</strong>
        <span>Dev setup, tests, PR workflow</span>
      </a>
    </div>

    <h2>Why PRAANA?</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th></th>
          <th>Typical transcript agent</th>
          <th>PRAANA</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Long sessions</strong></td>
          <td>Full history in prompt; context fills up</td>
          <td>Opt-in <strong>engine mode</strong>: tiered working memory, distillation, checkpoint</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Next day</strong></td>
          <td>Starts cold unless you paste notes</td>
          <td><strong>Cognitive memory</strong>: ranked digest from past sessions (project + global scope)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Honesty</strong></td>
          <td>Often marketed as solved</td>
          <td>
            <a href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana#known-limitations-honest">Known limitations</a>
            published upfront — no benchmark claims we can't back
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Community</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana/discussions">GitHub Discussions</a> — Q&amp;A, ideas, releases</li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana/issues">Issues</a> — bugs and feature tracking</li>
      <li><a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/praana">npm</a> — <code>npm install -g praana</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <h3>What is PRAANA?</h3>
    <p>
      PRAANA is an open-source terminal coding agent. It runs in your CLI, calls an LLM,
      executes tools (code search, multi-file edits with diff preview, optional shell),
      keeps long sessions usable with adaptive context, and remembers useful learnings
      across sessions in a local database.
    </p>
    <h3>Which LLM providers does it work with?</h3>
    <p>
      Anthropic (Claude), OpenAI (GPT), DeepSeek, Groq, Google (Gemini), Mistral, xAI,
      Fireworks, Together, OpenCode, and OpenRouter — plus Ollama for fully local models.
      PRAANA auto-detects your provider API key from the environment.
    </p>
    <h3>How is it different from a plain transcript coding agent?</h3>
    <p>
      Two things. An opt-in <strong>engine mode</strong> keeps long sessions on track with
      tiered working memory and tool-output distillation instead of stuffing the full
      history into the prompt. And optional <strong>cognitive memory</strong> extracts
      learnings when a session ends and surfaces a ranked digest at the start of the next.
      We publish <a href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana#known-limitations-honest">known limitations</a> upfront and make no benchmark claims we can't back.
    </p>
    <h3>Is it free and open source?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes. PRAANA is MIT-licensed, the source is on
      <a href="https://github.com/amitkumardubey/praana">GitHub</a>, and it's published on
      <a href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/praana">npm</a>: <code>bunx praana</code> or <code>bun add -g praana</code>.
    </p>
    <h3>Does my data leave my machine?</h3>
    <p>
      PRAANA is local-first. Cognitive memory lives in a local SQLite database on your
      machine. The only network calls are to the LLM provider you choose — or none at all
      if you run a local model with Ollama.
    </p>
    <h3>What do I need to run it?</h3>
    <p>
      Bun ≥ 1.2 (<a href="https://bun.sh/install">bun.sh/install</a>) and an API key for any supported provider (or Ollama for fully local use).
    </p>
  </div>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqStructuredData)} />
</Layout>
